  "prompt": "How are polar covalent bonds formed?",
  "response": "Polar covalent bonds are formed when two atoms with different electronegativities share electrons unequally. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Electronegativity difference\n- Occurs between atoms with different abilities to attract electrons\n- Greater electronegativity difference results in more polar bond\n\n2. Electron sharing process\n- Atoms share electrons, but not equally\n- More electronegative atom pulls electrons closer\n- Creates partial negative charge (\u03b4-) on more electronegative atom\n- Creates partial positive charge (\u03b4+) on less electronegative atom\n\n3. Example: Water molecule (H2O)\n- Oxygen is more electronegative than hydrogen\n- Oxygen pulls electron pairs closer\n- Oxygen gains partial negative charge\n- Hydrogen atoms gain partial positive charge\n\n4. Factors influencing polarity\n- Difference in electronegativity\n- Number of shared electron pairs\n- Molecular geometry\n\n5. Characteristics\n- Unequal electron distribution\n- Creates dipole moment\n- Leads to hydrogen bonding\n- Influences molecular properties like solubility\n\nPolar covalent bonds are intermediate between pure covalent and ionic bonds, depending on the electronegativity difference between atoms.",
